With an estimated global population of more than 9.5 billion by 2050, significant advances in areas that generate Big Data, such as remote sensing, unmanned aircraft systems, crop sensing, phenomics, natural resources/ecology, and genomics will be required in order to feed the world. The BD Spokes "Digital Agriculture: Unmanned Aircraft Systems, Plant Sciences, and Education (UASPSE)" project addressed these issues by removing barriers to data harmonization and automation, establishing cross-hub consortium of plant sciences, phenomics, and genomics, enabling online coordination of information and enabling education and training at all levels of the digital agriculture workforce. To this end, the project established the website of DigitalAg.org, and conducted or promoted the following activities and programs:

Established the MBDH Digital Agriculture Community;
Awarded 9 start-up research projects through $5,000 mini-grants;
Funded travel to North American Plant Phenotyping Network (NAPPN) events;
Funded travel to enable collaborations and discussions with international partners in Canada, Japan, and Australia;
Offered online webinars such as Plant Phenomics Phridays, Metagenomics Mondays, and Unmanned Data Mondays;Organized discussion on the topic of Agricultural Carbon Sequestration;
Worked with non-profit organizations to develop tribal stakeholder engagement;
Supported Unmanned Aircraft Systems informational events for Ag Producers and stakeholders, known as the UAS Roadshow, in 7 states (ND, NE, KS, IA, MO, IL, &amp; OH) across Midwest;
Promoted the Digital Agriculture track offering of the Midwest Big Data Summer School held at ISU;
Hosted or supported regional conferences and workshops such as the annual MBDH Digital Agriculture Community All-hands meeting, the UASPSE Annual Regional Meetup, UNL Datapalooza Hackathon, and the Virtual Conference on Big Data Promises and Obstacles: Agricultural Data Ownership and Privacy (BDPO).


For those wishing to continue the Digital Agriculture discussion, information about the current activities and programs of the MBDH Digital Agriculture Community can found on the community’s website (https://digital.ag.iastate.edu/).

Invited papers based on the BDPO virtual workshop are available online through the Agronomy Journal publisher’s website (https://acsess.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/toc/14350645/2022/114/5).

